Here is the Terraform configuration to create an Amazon S3 Glacier Vault and manage its data lifecycle using a Vault Lock Policy.

**Note:** While "AWS Data Lifecycle Manager" is a specific service primarily used for EBS Snapshots and AMIs, S3 Glacier Vaults use **Vault Lock Policies** to enforce data retention (lifecycle) rules (e.g., preventing deletion before a set time). The configuration below implements the Vault Lock Policy to satisfy the lifecycle requirement for the Glacier Vault.

```hcl
# Get current AWS account ID to construct ARNs dynamically
data "aws_caller_identity" "current" {}

# Resource: Amazon S3 Glacier Vault
# This creates the durable storage instance for your archives.
resource "aws_glacier_vault" "example" {
  name = "example-glacier-vault"

  # Optional: Define tagging for cost allocation
  tags = {
    Environment = "Production"
    ManagedBy   = "Terraform"
  }
}

# Resource: Glacier Vault Lock Policy
# This acts as the "Lifecycle Manager" for the Vault by enforcing retention rules.
# It implements a WORM (Write Once, Read Many) model.
resource "aws_glacier_vault_lock" "policy" {
  vault_name = aws_glacier_vault.example.name

  # NOTE: In a production environment, set complete_lock to false only during testing.
  # Once set to true, the lock policy becomes immutable and cannot be deleted.
  complete_lock = false

  # The policy defines the lifecycle retention logic.
  # This example prevents deletion of any archive younger than 365 days.
  policy = <<EOF
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "Set-data-retention-lifecycle",
      "Effect": "Deny",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "glacier:DeleteArchive",
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:glacier:us-east-1:${data.aws_caller_identity.current.account_id}:vaults/${aws_glacier_vault.example.name}/*"
      ],
      "Condition": {
        "NumericLessThan": {
          "glacier:ArchiveAgeinDays": "365"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
EOF
}
